se we’re doing things that don’t require a lot of thought.” (A lawyer told me that his kind refer to the time-consuming task of document review as “chillable billables.”)"},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"4YrL45","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"Ideally, we would decompress from focused interludes with more obviously relaxing rote “work” such as puzzles or knitting. But pausing throughout the day to knit is not realistic for most workers. Populating a spreadsheet may be the closest thing we have to leisure."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyPullquote","placement":{"id":"8imcl0","alignment":"HANG_LEFT"},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyPullquote","quote":{"html":"“Those two extra hours can’t get replaced with genuine mental activity”"}},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"7yQmEE","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"Danielle Li, an associate professor at the MIT Sloan School of Management and a co-author of a paper called “Generative AI at Work,” said she finds busywork soothing in part because it catapults her into a “flow state,” but also because it allows her to keep up the performance of work while resting her mind. Li acknowledges that this is not “good,” per se. “If I didn’t feel the need to be working all the time, then I wouldn’t value that particular aspect of busywork. With busywork I can tell myself, ‘Yay, I’m working.’ ‘You’re earning your place in this world.’ But you’re not actually trying that hard.’”"},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"MMfOAq","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"Li said she would celebrate AI tools reducing three hours of labor to one hour of labor if she could then use one and a half of the two hours s